<h1>@HI{{naikotohanai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vnai{{}}<strong>@HI{{kotohanai}}</strong>
<li> @Aistem{{}}@HI{{kunai}}<strong>@HI{{kotohanai}}</strong>
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{ja}}<strong>@HI{{kotohanai}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{ja}}<strong>@HI{{kotohanai}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{naikotohanai}}</strong> is used to express a mild affirmative using a double negative. It can be translated
as "I cannot say that ~ never happens".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{kono@KJ{{environs}}ha@KJ{{summer^cool}}shikunaindesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{iya,@KJ{{cool}}shikunaikotomonaindesuga,@KJ{{time^noma}}hidoku@KJ{{sultry}}kunarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Isn't it cool around here during the summer?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Yes it <em>is</em> cool, but sometimes it gets terribly hot.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The alternative form <strong>@HI{{naikotomonai}}</strong> (with @HI{{ha}} replaced by @HI{{mo}})
has the same meaning but the assertion is weaker.
</p>

